  <entry>
    <title type="html"><![CDATA[The Famous Code Formatting Techniques]]></title>
    <link href="http://spyrous.github.io/blog/2014/08/31/hello-world/"/>
    <updated>2014-08-31T19:12:56+03:00</updated>
    <id>http://spyrous.github.io/blog/2014/08/31/hello-world</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>This topic bothered me a lot at the beginning of my programming journey. I wanted to find ‘the‘ best code formatting technique and stick with it so my code would be easy to read at any time. After a year or so it is obvious to me that there is no such technique. It&rsquo;s more of a personal taste.</p>

<p>So should we invest time to find an acceptable style ? The answer is yes.</p>

<p>Fortunately for us there are a few ‘official’ conventions that you can pick from and get by. You are free to customize them if you think that something doesn’t look pretty but I would suggest you to stick with the basics. Most of the programmers are used to reading these coding styles and they will be able to read, improve and respond to faults in your code in less time.</p>

<p>I would also encourage you to read through professional open source code like let&rsquo;s say guava  if you are a java programmer. Guava is a library made by google&rsquo;s professional software developers and it can give you a lot of hints and information about what is a good programming format and structure. This is just an example. There are endless sources of well-written code for every language around the web that can enhance your arsenal more than you think. Examine them and build your programming style around solid foundations before you start coding.<br /></p>

<p>Nevertheless your coding style comes second when you are involved in a programming project. You have to adapt to the style that everyone is writing. Although if you happen to start one on your own choose which technique will serve you and (if you happen to have) your colleagues best and keep it throughout it.</p>

<p>Here I introduce you a couple of sites that cover programming languages formatting techniques that are widely used today:</p>

<p>-> <a href="http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/html-css-techniques/top-15-best-practices-for-writing-super-readable-code/">http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/html-css-techniques/top-15-best-practices-for-writing-super-readable-code/</a></p>

<p>-> <a href="http://www.gnu.org/prep/standards/html_node/Formatting.html">http://www.gnu.org/prep/standards/html_node/Formatting.html</a></p>

<p>-> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_style">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_style</a></p>

<p><em>Below I represent a few of these formats:</em><br />
<strong>1. llvm project format</strong></p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
